# Observability Conventions

## Data Sources

| Data Type | Index Pattern | Source |
|---|---|---|
| APM traces | `traces-apm*` | Elastic APM agents |
| APM metrics | `metrics-apm*` | Elastic APM agents |
| APM errors | `logs-apm.error*` | Elastic APM agents |
| Logs | `logs-*` | Filebeat, Elastic Agent, Logstash |
| Metrics | `metrics-*` | Metricbeat, Elastic Agent |
| Synthetics | `synthetics-*` | Elastic Synthetics |

## APM Setup

When instrumenting applications:
- Use `setup_apm` tool to generate framework-specific instructions
- Prefer Elastic APM agents over OpenTelemetry SDK for full Kibana integration
- OpenTelemetry is supported — data lands in `metrics-generic.otel-*`, `traces-apm.rum-*` etc.
- Always set `service.name`, `service.version`, and `deployment.environment`

## Log Shipping

When shipping logs:
- Use `setup_log_shipping` to generate Filebeat/Agent config
- Use ECS (Elastic Common Schema) field names
- Key fields: `message`, `log.level`, `service.name`, `trace.id` (for APM correlation)
- For Docker: use the Docker input or autodiscover
- For Kubernetes: use the Kubernetes provider with autodiscover

## SLOs

When creating SLOs:
- Use `kibana_api` with `POST /api/observability/slos`
- SLI types: `sli.apm.transactionDuration`, `sli.apm.transactionErrorRate`, `sli.kql.custom`
- Always set a realistic `objective.target` (e.g., 99.9% for critical, 99.5% for standard)
- Create burn rate alerts after SLO creation using `create_alert_rule`

## Alert Rules

When creating alert rules:
- Use `create_alert_rule` for common patterns (threshold, anomaly)
- For custom: use `kibana_api` with `POST /api/alerting/rule`
- Group alerts by `service.name` or `host.name` to reduce noise
- Set appropriate `check_every` and `threshold` values — too sensitive = alert fatigue

## ES|QL for O11Y

Common patterns:
```esql
// Error rate by service
FROM logs-* | WHERE log.level == "error" | STATS errors = COUNT(*) BY service.name | SORT errors DESC

// P95 latency by service
FROM traces-apm* | STATS p95 = PERCENTILE(transaction.duration.us, 95) BY service.name

// Log volume trends
FROM logs-* | STATS count = COUNT(*) BY BUCKET(@timestamp, 1 hour) | SORT @timestamp
```
